 {"id":"charmed_rust-9e9","title":"[Derive] Implement #[state] attribute for render-triggering fields","description":"# [Derive] Implement #[state] attribute for render-triggering fields

**Parent Epic:** charmed_rust-jpq (Add Derive Macro for Model Trait)

## Objective

Implement the `#[state]` attribute that marks struct fields whose changes should trigger a re-render. This enables optimized rendering where only state changes cause view updates, similar to React's state management.

## Detailed Requirements

### 1. State Attribute Definition

```rust
// crates/bubbletea-macros/src/attributes.rs
use darling::FromField;

/// Field-level configuration for state tracking
#[derive(Debug, Default, FromField)]
#[darling(attributes(state))]
pub struct StateFieldArgs {
    pub ident: Option<syn::Ident>,
    pub ty: syn::Type,

    /// Mark this field as state (triggers re-render on change)
    #[darling(default)]
    pub tracked: bool,

    /// Custom comparison function for change detection
    #[darling(default)]
    pub eq: Option<syn::Path>,

    /// Skip this field in state change detection
    #[darling(default)]
    pub skip: bool,

    /// Debug: log state changes for this field
    #[darling(default)]
    pub debug: bool,
}
```

### 2. Usage Syntax

```rust
use bubbletea_macros::Model;

#[derive(Model)]
struct AppModel {
    // Basic state tracking - triggers render on change
    #[state]
    counter: i32,

    // State with custom equality
    #[state(eq = "float_approx_eq")]
    progress: f64,

    // Skip from state tracking (internal bookkeeping)
    #[state(skip)]
    last_tick: std::time::Instant,

    // Debug logging for this field
    #[state(debug)]
    selected_index: usize,

    // Non-state field (ignored in change detection)
    cache: HashMap<String, String>,
}

fn float_approx_eq(a: &f64, b: &f64) -> bool {
    (a - b).abs() < 0.001
}
```

### 3. Change Detection Code Generation

```rust
// crates/bubbletea-macros/src/state.rs
use quote::quote;
use proc_macro2::TokenStream;
use syn::Ident;

pub struct StateField {
    pub ident: Ident,
    pub ty: syn::Type,
    pub eq_fn: Option<syn::Path>,
    pub debug: bool,
}

/// Generate the state snapshot struct
pub fn generate_state_snapshot(
    struct_name: &Ident,
    fields: &[StateField],
) -> TokenStream {
    let snapshot_name = quote::format_ident!("{}StateSnapshot", struct_name);

    let field_defs: Vec<_> = fields.iter().map(|f| {
        let ident = &f.ident;
        let ty = &f.ty;
        quote! { #ident: #ty }
    }).collect();

    let field_clones: Vec<_> = fields.iter().map(|f| {
        let ident = &f.ident;
        quote! { #ident: self.#ident.clone() }
    }).collect();

    quote! {
        #[derive(Clone)]
        struct #snapshot_name {
            #(#field_defs),*
        }

        impl #struct_name {
            fn __snapshot_state(&self) -> #snapshot_name {
                #snapshot_name {
                    #(#field_clones),*
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

/// Generate state comparison method
pub fn generate_state_changed(
    struct_name: &Ident,
    fields: &[StateField],
) -> TokenStream {
    let snapshot_name = quote::format_ident!("{}StateSnapshot", struct_name);

    let comparisons: Vec<_> = fields.iter().map(|f| {
        let ident = &f.ident;
        let debug_log = if f.debug {
            quote! {
                if changed {
                    charmed_log::debug!(
                        "State change detected: {}.{} changed",
                        stringify!(#struct_name),
                        stringify!(#ident)
                    );
                }
            }
        } else {
            quote! {}
        };

        if let Some(eq_fn) = &f.eq_fn {
            quote! {
                {
                    let changed = !#eq_fn(&self.#ident, &prev.#ident);
                    #debug_log
                    changed
                }
            }
        } else {
            quote! {
                {
                    let changed = self.#ident != prev.#ident;
                    #debug_log
                    changed
                }
            }
        }
    }).collect();

    quote! {
        impl #struct_name {
            fn __state_changed(&self, prev: &#snapshot_name) -> bool {
                #(#comparisons)||*
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### 4. Integration with Update Cycle

```rust
// Generated code wraps update to track state changes
pub fn generate_update_wrapper(
    struct_name: &Ident,
    original_update: &syn::Block,
) -> TokenStream {
    quote! {
        fn update(&mut self, msg: Self::Message) -> bubbletea::Command<Self::Message> {
            let prev_state = self.__snapshot_state();

            // Original update logic
            let cmd = { #original_update };

            // Check if render needed
            if self.__state_changed(&prev_state) {
                // Signal that view needs refresh
                self.__needs_render = true;
            }

            cmd
        }
    }
}
```

### 5. Field Type Requirements

```rust
// crates/bubbletea-macros/src/state.rs

use syn::{Type, spanned::Spanned};
use proc_macro_error::emit_warning;

/// Validate that state fields implement necessary traits
pub fn validate_state_field(field: &StateField) -> Result<(), syn::Error> {
    // Fields need Clone for snapshot
    // Fields need PartialEq OR custom eq function

    // Note: We can't fully validate trait bounds at macro time,
    // but we can emit helpful diagnostics

    if field.eq_fn.is_none() {
        // Will rely on PartialEq, emit a note
        emit_warning!(
            field.ident.span(),
            "State field '{}' requires PartialEq for change detection; \
             use #[state(eq = \"custom_fn\")] for custom comparison",
            field.ident
        );
    }

    Ok(())
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

1. [ ] `#[state]` attribute marks fields for change tracking
2. [ ] State snapshot struct generated automatically
3. [ ] Change detection via PartialEq by default
4. [ ] Custom equality functions via `#[state(eq = "fn_name")]`
5. [ ] `#[state(skip)]` excludes fields from tracking
6. [ ] `#[state(debug)]` enables change logging
7. [ ] Generated code compiles without Clone/PartialEq warnings
8. [ ] Performance: Only snapshot tracked fields, not entire struct
9. [ ] Works with generic structs: `Counter<T>` where `T: Clone + PartialEq`
10. [ ] Clear error when #[state] used on field without Clone

## Implementation Notes

### Performance Considerations

1. **Selective Cloning**: Only clone `#[state]` fields, not entire struct
2. **Lazy Evaluation**: Use short-circuit `||` for comparisons
3. **Inline Hints**: Mark generated methods `#[inline]` for optimization

```rust
#[inline]
fn __state_changed(&self, prev: &Self::StateSnapshot) -> bool {
    self.field1 != prev.field1 || self.field2 != prev.field2
}
```

### Type Complexity

Handle complex types gracefully:
```rust
#[derive(Model)]
struct App {
    #[state]
    items: Vec<Item>,  // Requires Vec<Item>: Clone + PartialEq

    #[state(eq = "rc_ptr_eq")]
    shared: Rc<RefCell<Data>>,  // Use pointer equality
}

fn rc_ptr_eq<T>(a: &Rc<T>, b: &Rc<T>) -> bool {
    Rc::ptr_eq(a, b)
}
```

### Generic Structs

```rust
#[derive(Model)]
struct Counter<T: Clone + PartialEq + Default> {
    #[state]
    value: T,
}

// Generated:
impl<T: Clone + PartialEq + Default> Counter<T> {
    fn __snapshot_state(&self) -> CounterStateSnapshot<T> { ... }
}
```

## Logging Requirements

Debug logging for state changes (when `#[state(debug)]` is used):

